  "Newton's law of universal gravitation": "",
  "The germ theory of disease transmission": "",
  "The cell theory in modern biology studies": "",
  "Newton's law of universal gravitation is a scientific law. It describes the pattern that all objects with mass attract each other with a force proportional to their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.": "",
  "Is a scientific theory just a guess?": "",
  "Yes, theories are just educated guesses with no supporting evidence at all": "",
  "No, a theory is well-tested and supported by a large body of evidence": "",
  "Yes, theories are personal opinions that scientists share with each other": "",
  "No, but theories are less reliable than hypotheses in scientific research": "",
  "In everyday language, 'theory' means a guess, but in science a theory is a well-substantiated explanation supported by extensive evidence from many experiments and observations. Scientific theories are among the most reliable forms of scientific knowledge.": "",
  "Can scientific theories change over time?": "",
  "No, once established, scientific theories can never be modified at all": "",
  "Yes, theories can be revised or replaced when new evidence is discovered": "",
  "No, changing a theory would destroy all of science and its foundations": "",
  "Yes, but only if the majority of people vote to change the theory itself": "",
  "Scientific theories can be modified or replaced when new evidence is found that contradicts them. This is a strength of science — it is self-correcting and always open to revision based on evidence.": "",
  "What is the main difference between a law and a theory?": "",
  "A law describes what happens; a theory explains why it happens": "",
  "A law is always correct; a theory is always incorrect in science": "",
  "A law is a guess; a theory is a fact that has been proven true": "",
  "A law is newer; a theory is an older version of the same idea": "",
  "Laws describe patterns (what happens), like 'objects fall toward Earth.' Theories explain mechanisms (why it happens), like 'mass curves spacetime, which causes gravitational attraction.' Both are equally important.": "",
  "Which of the following is a scientific theory?": "",
  "The law of conservation of energy in a closed system": "",
  "The theory of plate tectonics that explains Earth's surface movements": "",
  "Newton's first law of motion about objects at rest and in motion": "",
  "Ohm's law relating voltage, current, and resistance in circuits": "",
  "The theory of plate tectonics is a scientific theory. It explains why earthquakes occur, why mountains form, and why continents move by describing the movement of large plates on Earth's surface.": "",
  "What do scientific laws and theories have in common?": "",
  "Both are supported by extensive scientific evidence and testing": "",
  "Both are just guesses that have not been tested or verified yet": "",
  "Both explain why natural phenomena occur in the world around us": "",
  "Both describe patterns without explaining the underlying causes": "",
  "Both laws and theories are well-tested and supported by extensive evidence. Neither is a guess. The key difference is their purpose: laws describe patterns, and theories explain the underlying reasons.": "",
  "The law of conservation of mass states that mass is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction. What type of scientific knowledge is this?": "",
  "A hypothesis": "",
  "A scientific law": "",
  "A scientific theory": "",
