  "The law only applies to experiments conducted in university laboratories": "",
  "The law is accepted by everyone and can never be questioned by anyone": "",
  "When a scientific law is described as universal, it means it applies everywhere — on Earth, on Mars, or in distant galaxies. The law of gravity, for example, governs the motion of all objects with mass everywhere in the universe.": "",
  "What does 'supported by evidence' mean for theories and laws?": "",
  "Data from experiments and observations consistently agrees with the claim": "",
  "A single scientist says the claim is true based on personal experience": "",
  "A group of people voted that the claim should be accepted as valid": "",
  "The claim was written in a very old textbook and has not been updated": "",
  "Being 'supported by evidence' means that data collected from many experiments and observations consistently agrees with the theory or law. The more evidence that supports it, the more confidence scientists have.": "",
  "What does 'falsifiable' mean in science?": "",
  "A claim that could potentially be proven wrong by evidence or experiments": "",
  "A claim that is definitely false and has already been disproven by scientists": "",
  "A claim that is completely made up and based on no observations at all": "",
  "A claim that has been tested so many times that it can never be questioned": "",
  "Falsifiable means a claim can potentially be disproven by evidence. This is a requirement for scientific theories and hypotheses. If something cannot possibly be proven wrong, it is not considered scientific.": "",
  "What does 'scientific consensus' mean?": "",
  "The general agreement among scientists based on the weight of available evidence": "",
  "A formal vote taken by all scientists in the world to decide what is true": "",
  "The opinion of the most famous scientist in a particular field of study": "",
  "A rule that prevents scientists from disagreeing with one another publicly": "",
  "Scientific consensus is the collective judgment of experts in a field, based on the accumulated evidence. It does not mean 100% agreement, but rather that the vast majority of evidence supports a particular conclusion.": "",
  "What does 'paradigm shift' mean in science?": "",
